props.synopsis: The Bureau of Meteorology formally declares an El Niño weather event, months after the World Meteorological Organization announced the same. Follow live.

title.children: Bureau of Meteorology formally declares El Niño weather event as hot and dry conditions sweep south-east Australia

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Prime Minister Anthony Albanese will meet with emergency services personnel and experts next week. "This is because we've anticipated this coming," he said following the El Niño announcement. "The warnings are there. The science is there that our climate is changing. "And unfortunately, we are seeing that on the ground as we saw during the summer of 2019-2020." He said the government is working to mitigate risks in the short term but urged people to "follow advice when it is given". "I also want to pay tribute to those people who work in the community, the volunteers like the SES and others, emergency services personnel, who are always there for us at different times. And the projection of this summer is that it is going to be a difficult period."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: PM: 'It is going to be a difficult period'

children.content: Prime Minister Anthony Albanese will meet with emergency services personnel and experts next week.
"This is because we've anticipated this coming," he said following the El Niño announcement.
"The warnings are there. The science is there that our climate is changing.
"And unfortunately, we are seeing that on the ground as we saw during the summer of 2019-2020."
He said the government is working to mitigate risks in the short term but urged people to "follow advice when it is given".

"I also want to pay tribute to those people who work in the community, the volunteers like the SES and others, emergency services personnel, who are always there for us at different times. And the projection of this summer is that it is going to be a difficult period."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Craig: Does the recent and protracted La Niña period mean there'll be an equally protracted El Niño period? Here's ABC meteorologist Tom Saunders: The recent three-year La Niña does not increase the risk of a multi-year El Niño. Most El Niño's only last one year (6-9 months to be precise), but very occasionally can last two to three years.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Will the El Niño be longer than normal?
